verbose_text: Thus, we estimate proximal cysteines account for 10.7% of the total N acetylation load that occurs on liver proteins in vivo, with other mechanisms, such as association of acetyl-CoA with the surface of proteins, intermolecular S--> S--> N-acetyl transfer reactions, and direct N acetylation, also contributing to acetylation load.
evidence: intermolecular S-->S-->N-acetyl transfer reactions, and direct N-acetylation
